  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why astronauts have a white and an orange-coloured space suit?",
  "response": "Astronauts wear different-colored spacesuits tailored to specific phases of their missions, primarily **white** and **orange** suits, each serving distinct purposes:\n\n### **1. White Spacesuits for Extravehicular Activities (EVAs)**\n- **Purpose:** These suits are designed for spacewalks, allowing astronauts to perform tasks outside the spacecraft.\n- **Design Features:**\n  - **Thermal Control:** White reflects sunlight, helping to manage the extreme temperatures of space by keeping the astronaut cooler in direct sunlight and providing insulation against the cold.\n  - **Visibility and Identification:** The white color stands out against the blackness of space and the backdrop of Earth, making astronauts easily identifiable to mission control and other crew members.\n  - **Protection:** These suits provide a pressurized environment, oxygen supply, and shielding from micrometeoroids and radiation.\n\n### **2. Orange-Colored Suits for Launch and Landing (Launch/Entry Suits)**\n- **Purpose:** Bright orange suits are typically worn during the critical phases of **launch** and **re-entry/landing** when astronauts are still inside the spacecraft or in the event of an emergency evacuation.\n- **Design Features:**\n  - **High Visibility:** The bright orange color ensures that astronauts are easily spotted in rescue operations, especially if an emergency landing occurs in water or remote areas.\n  - **Safety:** Often made from fire-resistant materials, these suits provide an added layer of protection during the high-stress launch and landing processes.\n  - **Mobility:** Designed to allow ease of movement within the confined spaces of the spacecraft while still offering necessary safety features.\n\n### **Summary**\n- **White Suits:** Optimized for the harsh environment of space during EVAs, focusing on thermal management, protection, and visibility in the extraterrestrial setting.\n- **Orange Suits:** Focused on safety and visibility during the high-risk launch and landing phases, ensuring astronauts can be quickly located and rescued if needed.\n\nBy using these distinct color schemes and suit designs, space agencies like NASA enhance the safety and efficiency of astronauts throughout all stages of their missions.",
